{
  "text": "In presenting the hormone to DNA, a receptor employing a ligand binding domain is nominally deployed. In Figure 3 (a), the cortisol molecule is depicted surrounding by the amino acid groups comprising the LBD, with hydrogen bonding as the mechanism to keep the unit secured. However, hydrogen bonding seems a little weak considering that the complex has to undergo potential nuclear translocation, as well as docking and gene transcription -seems a lot to ask for hydrogen bonds, especially considering that there are only four or five of them in the key complex connections. As I have noted in [CITATION_1] , stability can be enhanced with the addition of calcium ions, which is also consistent with the entry of these ions in tandem with steroid hormone molecules, such as cortisol, entering the cell. With the calcium ions, the overall structure of the cortisol-Ca 2+ -LBD complex is shown in Figure 3 (b).",
